<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1895-12-23T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1895-12-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="335" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d335">
                            <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Olney</persName> to
                                    Mr. <persName type="to">Eustis</persName></hi>.</head>
                            <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg></opener>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1895-12-23"><hi rend="italic">December 23,
                                        1895</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                            <p>Your No. 421 received. Is not sentence stating D. and P. to have been
                                identified as Draper and Purdy a mistake? American citizens supposed
                                to have been referred to were Dupuy and Poupard. Bray, Mrs. Waller,
                                Consul Wetter, all declare their ignorance of any such persons as
                                Draper and Purdy. See Consul Wetter’s letter, copy of which has been
                                sent you, of April 20.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Olney</hi></signed>.</closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>